    <rigor-hint>FULL</rigor-hint>
    <rigor-reason>Modifies existing middleware (.cs file) that runs on every authenticated request; tags include bff-api/ai; touches the audit choke point per ADR-015; G6 acceptance gate (every Tool dispatch writes audit) verified here</rigor-reason>
    <parallel-group>D</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
    <parallel-reason>Edits Infrastructure/Logging/AuditEnrichmentMiddleware.cs — disjoint from task 041 (Services/Ai/ActionEngine/) and task 042 (Services/Jobs/). Touches the audit middleware which is module-disjoint from the orchestrator and job-handler code.</parallel-reason>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Extend the existing `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/Logging/AuditEnrichmentMiddleware.cs` (and the supporting `IAuditLogService` + `AuditLogService` + `AuditEntry` types) to add Tool-dispatch enrichment fields per ADR-015: Tier 2 hash-only entries (compliance) and Tier 3 Cosmos work history (tenant-scoped, GDPR erasure path). The middleware ALREADY enriches every authenticated request with `oid` / `appid` / `obo` / `tenantId` / `correlationId`; this task adds the Tool-dispatch-specific fields (`actionId`, `runId`, `toolId`, `phase`, `gateDecision`) when an Action Engine handler is on the request path. This is the G6 acceptance gate: every Tool dispatch writes audit (ADR-015 Tier 2 + Tier 3) — verified by audit middleware integration test.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    SPAARKE BFF audit + observability engineer fluent in ADR-015 AI Data Governance (Tier 2 hash-only / Tier 3 Cosmos work history / tenant scoping / GDPR erasure), the existing `AuditEnrichmentMiddleware` shape, and Cosmos partitioning patterns. You add fields that are useful for incident response without leaking content (no prompts, no model responses, no document bytes — hash only).
  </role>

  <goal>
    Concrete artifacts:
    1. **`Infrastructure/Logging/AuditEnrichmentMiddleware.cs`** (edit existing) — add Tool-dispatch enrichment fields to the `BeginScope` dictionary when the request is on an Action Engine path. New fields (only populated when set by the orchestrator / Tool registry): `actionId` (Guid string), `runId` (Guid string), `toolId` (string), `phase` (string — `authoring | schedule | execute | approve | deliver`), `gateDecision` (string — `Approved | Rejected | TimedOut | Pending | NotRequired`). Fields stay null when not applicable so non-AE requests are untouched.
    2. **`Services/Ai/Audit/AuditEntry.cs`** (edit existing) — add new fields for the Tool-dispatch shape: `ActionId`, `RunId`, `ToolId`, `Phase`, `GateDecision`, plus `ContentHash` (SHA-256 over the Tool's input + output blobs — for Tier 2 compliance) and `TenantId` (mandatory for Tier 3 partition key).
    3. **`Services/Ai/Audit/AuditLogService.cs`** (edit existing) — extend `WriteAsync` to support two-tier emission: (a) Tier 2 hash-only entry to the existing audit sink (no Tool content); (b) Tier 3 entry to Cosmos work history, partitioned by `tenantId`, with the Tool dispatch details (still hash, not raw content). Add `DeleteWorkHistoryForTenantAsync(tenantId, ct)` for GDPR erasure path.
    4. **Tool-dispatch event emission** — confirm `IToolHandlerRegistry` (task 026) writes the per-dispatch audit. THIS task extends the audit ENTRY shape and the middleware scope; the registry remains the audit choke point per ADR-015. The integration test (Step 8) confirms the registry → audit service → middleware enrichment → Tier 2 + Tier 3 emission path is complete.
    5. **GDPR erasure verification** — unit test asserts that `DeleteWorkHistoryForTenantAsync(tenantId, ct)` removes ALL Tier 3 entries for a tenant while leaving other tenants' entries untouched.
    6. **G6 verification artifact** — integration test `tests/integration/Sprk.Bff.Api.IntegrationTests/ActionEngine/AuditEnrichmentIntegrationTests.cs` runs a Tool dispatch end-to-end and asserts both Tier 2 (hash-only audit entry) and Tier 3 (Cosmos work history entry) are written with the expected fields and NO content / prompt / response verbatim.

    Acceptance: G6 integration test passes; GDPR erasure test passes; the middleware scope includes the new fields only when the orchestrator sets them via `IActionExecutionContextAccessor` (a thin accessor service — add if not already present).
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      ADR-015 (AI Data Governance) requires that EVERY AI invocation writes audit: Tier 1 (request/response telemetry, not content), Tier 2 (hash-only — for compliance and audit-trail integrity, no content), Tier 3 (Cosmos work history — tenant-scoped, supports GDPR erasure). The Action Engine's Tool dispatch is an AI invocation in the broadest sense (any Tool — Deterministic, AI, Hybrid — gets audited identically per the spec).

      The existing `AuditEnrichmentMiddleware` at `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/Logging/AuditEnrichmentMiddleware.cs` enriches every AUTHENTICATED request with `oid` / `appid` / `obo` / `tenantId` / `correlationId` (canonical Auth v2 fields per ADR-028). It does NOT yet know about Action Engine concerns. This task adds the fields that make Tool-dispatch audit useful for incident response without leaking content.

      ADR-015 explicit rules:
      - MUST log only identifiers, sizes, timings, outcome codes
      - MUST NOT log document contents, prompts, or model responses verbatim
      - MUST NOT store verbatim AI response in Tier 2 audit (hash only)
      - MUST scope all persisted AI artifacts by tenant

      The Tool-dispatch audit is written by `IToolHandlerRegistry` (task 026 — the audit choke point). This task does NOT add a new audit writer — it (a) extends the entry shape, (b) enriches the middleware scope so request-level fields propagate, (c) adds two-tier emission to the audit service.

      `IActionExecutionContextAccessor` is a small `AsyncLocal&lt;ActionExecutionContext&gt;` shim (similar to `IHttpContextAccessor`) that the orchestrator sets at run start and the middleware reads to enrich the scope. If task 041 already created it, reuse; otherwise add it here as part of the field-propagation plumbing.

      Cosmos work history container: per ADR-015 + plan.md, partition by `tenantId`. Index on `actionId`, `runId`, `toolId`, `timestamp`. GDPR erasure path: delete all entries with partition key = `tenantId`. The Cosmos client itself is already wired in the BFF (existing audit infrastructure); this task adds the Action-Engine-specific entry shape and erasure method.

      G6 acceptance gate: Every Tool dispatch writes audit (ADR-015 Tier 2 + Tier 3) — verified by audit middleware integration test (G6). This task is where G6 is established.

      Binding governance: `.claude/constraints/bff-extensions.md` MUST be loaded. Placement = BFF. No new NuGet packages.
    </background>
