  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion testable="true">**G6 acceptance gate** — Every Tool dispatch writes audit (ADR-015 Tier 2 + Tier 3) — verified by audit middleware integration test (G6). The integration test at `tests/integration/Sprk.Bff.Api.IntegrationTests/ActionEngine/AuditEnrichmentIntegrationTests.cs` passes.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Tier 2 audit entry is hash-only — assertion: the entry's serialized JSON contains `ContentHash` but does NOT contain the raw Tool input/output (test inspects the entry contents).</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Tier 3 Cosmos work history entry is tenant-partitioned — assertion: the document's partition key equals the request's `tenantId`; querying with a different tenant id returns no results.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">GDPR erasure path works — `DeleteWorkHistoryForTenantAsync(tenantA, ct)` deletes ALL tenant A entries; tenant B entries remain unaffected.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Non-Action-Engine requests are unaffected — assertion: a request to a non-AE endpoint (e.g., `/healthz`, `/api/document/...`) produces no `actionId`/`runId`/`toolId` fields in the log scope; existing audit shape preserved.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`IActionExecutionContextAccessor` is set by the orchestrator (task 041) and read by the middleware; verified by integration test that asserts fields propagate correctly during a Tool dispatch.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">Audit-sink failure does not bubble — if Cosmos write fails, the request continues; failure is logged but does not return 500 to the caller.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`notes/decisions/task-043-bff-extensions-checklist.md` exists with every `bff-extensions.md` pre-merge item answered.</criterion>
    <criterion testable="true">`dotnet list package --vulnerable --include-transitive` returns no NEW HIGH-severity CVE.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>

  <notes>
    The `AuditEnrichmentMiddleware` lives at `src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/Logging/AuditEnrichmentMiddleware.cs` — NOT `Services/Ai/Audit/` as some older docs may say. The `Services/Ai/Audit/` folder holds `IAuditLogService` + `AuditLogService` + `AuditEntry` + `AuditHashHelper` (the data + writer side). This task touches BOTH the middleware (scope enrichment) and the audit service (two-tier emission + erasure method).

    ADR-015's binding rule "MUST NOT store verbatim AI response in Tier 2 audit (hash only)" is the load-bearing constraint. If the Tier 2 entry contains raw Tool input or output, the implementation is wrong. Use `AuditHashHelper` (existing) to compute the hash; store the hash only.

    Tier 3 Cosmos work history is for incident response and forensic audit. It MAY contain Tool input/output if explicitly classified as "low-sensitivity" per the Tool's metadata, but the SAFE default is hash-only. For MVP, ALL Tier 3 entries are hash-only. Lift this restriction in R2 with explicit per-Tool classification.

    GDPR erasure: the partition-key-based delete is efficient at Cosmos scale. Do NOT iterate documents and delete one-by-one — use the partition delete API. If the existing Cosmos client wrapper doesn't expose this, add it now (cheap addition).

    The G6 integration test is the verification surface. If you can't get the integration test green, the task is not done. Don't skip it.

    `IToolHandlerRegistry` (task 026) is the audit choke point — every Tool dispatch goes through it, every dispatch writes audit. This task makes the audit ENTRY useful for incident response by adding the AE-specific fields. The choke point itself was established in task 026.
  </notes>

